## Setting 1: Four-Prong Solitaire (from $690)

[![Petite emerald cut solitaire diamond ring in 14K yellow gold](https://ion.bluenile.com/sets/Jewelry/Photoshoot/Bluenile/LifeStyleV4/DiamondBasics/606580/606580_EMR_0100CT_Y_2_1600X1600.jpg)](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry?ComponentIDs=Ring&Diamonds=Dia&stoneShape=emerald&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

The four-prong solitaire is the standard setting for an emerald cut diamond and the right starting point for most buyers. Four prongs — one at each long corner — hold the stone with the minimum amount of metal. The long sides of the stone are completely open to the light.

What you get with a solitaire: maximum light return, the cleanest possible rectangular outline, and zero competition between the setting and the stone. The band disappears under the stone. All you see is the diamond.

The downside is corner exposure. Four-prong solitaires cover the angled corner facets, but the metal prong is thin. A well-made solitaire is safe for daily wear — just check that the prongs are rounded rather than pointed, which reduces snagging.

