The petite solitaires at [$690](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/rings/petite-emerald-cut-solitaire-diamond-ring-in-14k-yellow-gold-by-james-allen-item-311196?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) are the entry point — a narrow band, four prongs, nothing else. They work best when the center stone is 1ct or above. At under 1ct, the band can visually overpower a small stone.

The knife edge solitaire at [$925](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/knife-edge-solitaire-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-by-james-allen-item-316048?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) adds a slight ridge along the top edge of the shank, which catches the light and makes the band look thinner than it is. This works well for emerald cuts because the vertical lines of the shank echo the vertical step facets of the stone.

For platinum, the classic four-prong at [$1,180](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/classic-four-prong-solitaire-engagement-ring-in-platinum-item-194156?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the strongest prong-hold option in the solitaire category. Platinum prongs don't wear down as fast as gold, which matters for an active lifestyle.

