## Setting 2: East-West Solitaire (from $1,400)

[![Emerald cut diamond in east-west setting, yellow gold](https://ion.bluenile.com/sets/Jewelry/Photoshoot/Bluenile/BrioPackshotBox/Rings/501150/501150_M1_EMR_DIM_wht_0100CT_Y_Box5_003_1600X1600.jpg)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?MetalType=all&Diamonds=Dia&ShapeID=Emerald&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

The east-west setting rotates the stone 90 degrees so the long axis runs across the finger instead of along it. This is a completely different look from the traditional solitaire. The stone reads wider than it does long, and the rectangular shape becomes more prominent from a head-on view.

The east-west works well on longer fingers where a traditional long-axis emerald cut can look narrow. Rotated 90 degrees, the same stone fills more of the visual width. It also works for buyers who want a modern, architectural look without the sparkle of a halo.

One thing to check with an east-west setting: the ratio of the stone. Emerald cuts in a 1.30 to 1.50 length-to-width ratio work best east-west. A very elongated stone (1.60 or above) can look awkwardly wide when rotated.

