The [$1,400 east-west platinum solitaire](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/east-west-knife-edge-cathedral-solitaire-engagement-ring-in-platinum-by-james-allen-item-311250?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the only dedicated east-west engagement ring setting in this dataset. Platinum is the right call for an east-west because the prongs are positioned at the short ends of the stone — the ends see more stress with an east-west orientation — and platinum's durability handles that better than gold.

The [east-west 7-stone bands at $2,510](https://www.bluenile.com/wedding-rings/east-west-7-stone-emerald-diamond-anniversary-ring-in-14k-yellow-gold-5-8-ct-tw-item-150312?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) are wedding bands, not engagement ring settings. They're listed here because they pair perfectly with a traditional solitaire — the horizontal line of the band echoes the long axis of the center stone.

