## Setting 3: Pavé Band (from $1,325)

[![Emerald cut diamond ring in rose gold pavé setting, lifestyle shot](https://ion.bluenile.com/sets/Jewelry/Photoshoot/Bluenile/LifeStyle/DiamondBasics/606747/606747_EMR_0200CT_R_2_1600X1600.jpg)](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry?ComponentIDs=Ring&Diamonds=Dia&stoneShape=emerald&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

The pavé band adds a row of small melee diamonds along the shank of the ring. Done correctly, this adds sparkle to the band without competing with the center stone. The melee diamonds stay below the center stone's table, so the step facets still read clean.

This is the most popular upgrade from a plain solitaire. The additional sparkle makes the ring look more complete — the center stone has context instead of sitting alone on a plain metal band. It also catches the light from different angles, including when you look at the ring side-on.

The key difference between pavé types: micropavé uses very small stones set close together (more refined, more labor intensive); common prong pavé uses slightly larger stones in a shared-prong system (stronger hold, more sparkle per carat weight).

[![Emerald cut diamond ring with diamond pavé band, white gold](https://ion.bluenile.com/sets/Jewelry/Photoshoot/Bluenile/BrioPackshotBox/Rings/505132/505132_M1_EMR_DIM_wht_0100CT_R_Box4_004_1600X1600.jpg)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?MetalType=all&Diamonds=Dia&ShapeID=Emerald&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

