The [$2,090 common prong pavé](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/common-prong-diamond-pave-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-by-james-allen-item-310923?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) has a fuller pavé coverage. The diamonds are slightly larger and the effect is more pronounced. For center stones above 2ct, this level of setting presence is proportionate.

> "The pavé band is the most common request I see from emerald cut buyers who want a little more ring but don't want the halo. It's a good instinct — the sparkle runs alongside the stone, not around it. The center stone still owns the stage." — Farzana, diamond advisor

---

## The Corner Exposure Problem

Every emerald cut diamond has eight corners. Six of them — the long edges and the short ends — have natural facets running into them. The other two pairs of corners are trimmed at an angle, which is called a chamfered corner or a cut corner. Those chamfered corners are the weakest point of the stone.

When a setting's prong covers the corner completely, the metal absorbs any impact. When the prong sits slightly inside the corner — or when there's no prong at the corner at all — the trimmed facet is exposed. One hard knock against a countertop can chip it.

This is The Corner Exposure Problem: the setting-to-corner interface is the single point of failure for an emerald cut diamond. Bezel settings solve it completely. Four-prong solitaires manage it if the prongs are correctly positioned. Halos make it worse, because the outer melee ring creates a gap between the prong and the edge of the stone.

Before you buy any setting, look at the corner coverage. In photos, you should be able to see the prong head overlapping the chamfered corner from a top-down view. If the chamfered corner is visible between the prong and the stone's edge, that setting has inadequate corner protection.

