## Setting 4: Bezel (from $990)

[![Emerald cut diamond in white gold bezel setting](https://ion.bluenile.com/sets/Jewelry/Photoshoot/Bluenile/BrioSuperImposeBox/Rings/505031/505031_M1_EMR_DIM_wht_0100CT_W_Box2_004_1600X1600.jpg)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?MetalType=all&Diamonds=Dia&ShapeID=Emerald&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

A bezel setting wraps a rim of metal around the girdle of the stone. The stone sits inside a metal collar that holds it on all sides — including every corner. This is the safest setting for an emerald cut diamond and the correct choice for an active lifestyle.

The bezel does two things well: it protects all eight corners, and it adds a clean geometric frame that complements the rectangular outline of the stone. The metal rim echoes the shape. A well-made bezel on an emerald cut looks intentional, not protective.

The trade-off is light. A bezel blocks some light from entering the stone through the sides. An emerald cut already relies on its table for most of the light return, so the loss is less dramatic than on a brilliant cut — but you will notice less fire compared to a prong setting.

