## Metal Color and Band Width Guide

The metal color you choose has a visual impact on the center stone that most buyers discover only after the ring arrives. For emerald cuts specifically, the metal choice affects color perception more than on brilliant cuts.

A white metal (white gold or platinum) under a D-F color stone looks consistent — the colorless stone and the colorless metal match. Warm metals (yellow or rose gold) under an H-J color stone absorb any faint warmth in the stone and actually make the stone look more colorless to the eye. That's a legitimate reason to choose yellow gold over white if your center stone is in the H-J range.

<table class="dc-custom-table">
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Stone Color</th>
      <th>Best Metal Choice</th>
      <th>Why</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>D-F (colorless)</td>
      <td>Platinum or 18K White Gold</td>
      <td>Metal matches the stone — no warm contrast</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>G-H (near colorless)</td>
      <td>14K White Gold or Platinum</td>
      <td>Slight warmth absorbed by the cool metal</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>H-J (near colorless, faint)</td>
      <td>14K Yellow Gold or Rose Gold</td>
      <td>Warm metal masks faint yellow, stone reads more colorless</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Any color</td>
      <td>Platinum (durability priority)</td>
      <td>Hardest, longest-lasting, prongs don't wear down</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

Band width matters too. Emerald cuts are long and narrow. A very wide band (above 4mm) can crowd the stone's long edges visually. For stones under 1.5ct, a band between 1.5mm and 2.5mm is proportionate. For 2ct and above, bands between 2.5mm and 3.5mm work. Above 4ct, a 3.5mm to 4mm band balances the stone's footprint.

